[Student "S"]
{When using lebensohl, a 2NT bid over an enemy overcall asks partner to bid 3\C. So partner replies 3\C.  

When using lebensohl, a 2NT bid over an enemy overcall asks partner to bid 3\C. So partner replies 3\C. 

Now you complete the sequence by bidding 3NT. This says that not only do you think 3NT would be a good choice, but also that you have their \Ds stopped.

The contract would be 3NT played by West.

East plays 3NT. South leads the \DK. What will you play from dummy? (North follows with the \D2.

Winner List: \S = 0 : \H = 3 : \D = 1 : \C = 0 :: Total = 4

Since South has apparently led from \D K Q it seems you will get a second \D winner when they pursue the suit. You can also establish 3 more winners in \Cs. You can also establish 3 more winners in \Ss.

But as you can figure, you are going to have to establish <b>BOTH</b> black suits to get enough winners, and therein lies the problem. If South has a 5-card \D suit they will be able to establish 3 \D winners by the time you have knocked out both black Aces. In that case you cannot make the contract. Of course, if the \Ds are split 4-4 you will only lose 2 \Ds and the two black Aces. However South would probably not have overcalled a 4-card suit. 

But South might have a 6-card \D suit, leaving North with just 2. Assume the two black Aces are split, one with South and one with North. If you win the first trick with dummy's \DA you will be OK if you first play the black suit where South holds the Ace. He will take it and then establish his \Ds. No problem, because when you knock out North's black Ace he won't have a \D left. BUT, if you guess the wrong black suit first you will go down.

You can protect your interests fully just by letting South hold the first \D, then winning the second as cheaply as you can. At that point North will be out of \Ds so it won't matter which black suit you go for.

The Deal shows South with 6 \Ds to the K Q, the critical situation.

If you take dummy's \DA at the first trick you will succeed if you next attack \Ss, but you will fail if you next attack \Cs. 

But if you hold up on the first trick and win the continuation, you will succeed whichever black suit you attack next.

The holdup would of course fail if South held both black Aces, but in this case no Plan would succeed.}
[Play "W"]DK

